think of all of our roles as being research roles. That's something that's, I guess, exciting to me

00:07:07.540 --> 00:07:11.700
about the type of work that we do is you don't have to be in academia to be constantly doing

00:07:11.700 --> 00:07:16.179
test and learn research in this space. Oh, I look like they said they can jump in

00:07:16.179 --> 00:07:18.019
on the mic. Oh, great. Yeah.

00:07:18.980 --> 00:07:28.260
Good morning, all. So yeah, Jamie, so my situation was, I was actually an economist for the federal

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:32.660
government. I worked at the US Bureau of Labor Statistics, ended up really kind of falling in

00:07:32.660 --> 00:07:39.459
love with R and data science in general, started building out a lot of tools for them to use and

00:07:39.459 --> 00:07:43.619
all that, some of which are still in use, which is kind of a little doff of the cap to me, I guess.

00:07:43.700 --> 00:07:50.500
I'm pretty proud of that. But, you know, I ended up going in a direction that was more tech,

00:07:51.059 --> 00:07:55.059
that was more like data science, building tools and doing all that kind of stuff and found myself

00:07:55.059 --> 00:07:59.380
getting further and further away from the research and analysis stuff that I was doing. For example,

00:08:00.260 --> 00:08:08.660
I was publishing papers before doing research on macroeconomic trends and some other things. Also,

00:08:08.820 --> 00:08:16.500
consumer trends and things of that nature. And I kind of missed that research, research-y type

00:08:16.500 --> 00:08:23.380
of feel where I'm asking questions. You know, I always wanted to use data to ask and answer

00:08:23.380 --> 00:08:29.700
questions rather than to build tools, which is also a really important thing. But it's not,

00:08:29.700 --> 00:08:35.940
kind of, you know, my, it's not really my bag. So, you know, I kind of missed that.

00:08:36.900 --> 00:08:43.460
It's not really my bag. Yeah. So, yeah. So, this is, and that's helpful context. So,

00:08:44.340 --> 00:08:48.179
one of the things I would say is I would ask yourself, number one, if your job has to,

00:08:48.179 --> 00:08:53.219
has to fill all of that. So, I personally also love the research component. And one of the

00:08:53.219 --> 00:08:57.940
things about insurance and finance is we're not always using the most relevant techniques or the

00:08:57.940 --> 00:09:03.539
newest techniques in our stuff. And so, I have to stay abreast of that somehow. And we didn't

00:09:03.539 --> 00:09:08.659
talk about this in my intro, but I actually have a side gig, and that's teaching at Northeastern.

00:09:08.659 --> 00:09:14.099
And I teach data science courses there at the graduate level. And I also do research there.

00:09:14.099 --> 00:09:19.539
I have research grants that are active that I do with them as a side kind of thing. And that's

00:09:19.539 --> 00:09:24.099
what keeps me up to date. It kind of tickles that research fancy because especially if you're

00:09:24.099 --> 00:09:28.820
working in kind of a corporate environment, you're not going to be publishing papers about the work

00:09:28.820 --> 00:09:32.500
you're doing usually because your company wants to keep that secret. Like, that's your, that's

00:09:32.500 --> 00:09:38.820
your whole advantage. So, for me at least, one of the things that I did to kind of tickle that was

00:09:38.820 --> 00:09:44.419
to do work as an adjunct through a university or to help out on grants and like certain grants.

00:09:44.419 --> 00:09:48.580
And I won't be like the lead author or anything like that, but I'll be a side author. I'll get

00:09:48.580 --> 00:09:53.059
to do some of the analysis. I'll get to get in on some of those conversations. And I'll get to see

00:09:53.059 --> 00:09:58.820
the techniques that I could be applying in our space right as they're coming out. So, for me,

00:09:58.900 --> 00:10:02.979
that's, that's one way to do that. I know that might be a little bit higher barrier to entry,

00:10:02.979 --> 00:10:09.140
but kind of as I think more deeply about your question, I would also consider what roles within

00:10:09.140 --> 00:10:14.179
a company look like because there are roles that are very, very technical. And then there are data

00:10:14.179 --> 00:10:18.659
science roles that are more explaining things. And you might find that you enjoy the roles more

00:10:18.659 --> 00:10:22.979
that shift over toward the product side where you're really explaining and looking at the

00:10:22.979 --> 00:10:27.299
impact of the data and models, not just, you know, building them.

00:10:28.020 --> 00:10:32.739
Yeah, that's actually, that sounds more like kind of what I'm interested in doing. Cool.

00:10:32.739 --> 00:10:35.299
Thank you so much. I would look for product roles. Yeah, absolutely.

