team's needs fit into that bigger effort. I'm doing lots of hand-waving and I realize I'm not

00:10:59.140 --> 00:11:05.859
on video today. I'm curious how you fit into that effort and how you find your needs to

00:11:06.739 --> 00:11:13.539
like fit well or influence the broader thing. My experience is sometimes there's some tension and

00:11:13.539 --> 00:11:18.179
it's challenging to figure out how to balance all of those needs of a team versus a whole

00:11:18.179 --> 00:11:20.820
enterprise. And so just really curious about your experience there.

00:11:21.539 --> 00:11:26.500
Yeah, I would say something, and I saw another question in the chat kind of about my background

00:11:26.500 --> 00:11:30.900
training. And I would say something that I learned kind of going into those types of

00:11:30.900 --> 00:11:36.260
transformation projects. I did a similar one previously when I was at Lincoln, is you go

00:11:36.260 --> 00:11:41.219
from being like a data scientist or a data person to being what I would call half psychologist,

00:11:41.219 --> 00:11:47.700
half salesperson, where it's more about negotiating the change management and the

00:11:47.700 --> 00:11:54.340
emotions around the change than it is about the actual data. And I would say one of the things

00:11:54.340 --> 00:12:01.539
that is really helpful around that is that frequently IT is trying to make a change that's

00:12:01.539 --> 00:12:07.140
an important change and they need business leaders to help them drive that and find the use cases.

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:12.099
And frequently they have thought of some use cases, but maybe they aren't spot on just the

00:12:12.099 --> 00:12:15.700
same way as data scientists. Sometimes we'll think of a model and then the business will be like,

00:12:15.700 --> 00:12:19.940
that doesn't make any sense for this reason. The same thing is happening with IT. So

00:12:20.820 --> 00:12:25.460
I think the general experience tends to be that IT is trying to push this transformation or this

00:12:25.460 --> 00:12:29.940
move to cloud or this new technology, and they don't really know how it applies. And so I really

00:12:29.940 --> 00:12:34.739
love to grab onto that and be their biggest advocate. And then they become my biggest

00:12:34.739 --> 00:12:41.059
advocate. And that's really kind of how we drive the digital change forward. I would say, yes,

00:12:41.059 --> 00:12:46.820
it's a huge distinction between what team needs and what business needs. I tend to like to set

00:12:46.820 --> 00:12:51.299
the standards because then other people will just adopt them. It's easier to adopt someone else's

00:12:51.299 --> 00:12:56.099
standard than it is to make your own. So I love the ability to go first and make a best practice

00:12:56.099 --> 00:13:00.739
and then have other people just adopt it rather than having to argue that I don't think that

00:13:00.739 --> 00:13:05.460
that best practice might be the best one and try to switch it over. So I love to be a front runner.

00:13:06.900 --> 00:13:11.059
And that's actually one of the reasons I'm at Plymouth versus kind of the prior career I was

00:13:11.059 --> 00:13:16.739
at Lincoln. Great place. They love to be the kind of fast follower, not a driver. And Plymouth loves

00:13:16.739 --> 00:13:21.780
to be a driver. So that fits really well with my personality in terms of change and how we go

00:13:21.780 --> 00:13:28.020
forward. Did that answer your question? It really does. Thanks. I really like that note about being

00:13:28.020 --> 00:13:34.260
able to adapt early and be at the forefront of change as a way to be influential and

00:13:37.059 --> 00:13:41.380
really mercenarily about getting what you want and what you need into the conversation.

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:46.659
Yeah. And I think it's really about making other people feel good at the end of the day,

00:13:46.659 --> 00:13:51.059
like rewarding IT, showing them business value, and then they're able to go to their managers

00:13:51.059 --> 00:13:55.219
and show that. And then they're super loyal to you when you do that. Yeah, that's really neat.

