00:14:45.780 --> 00:14:49.539
So kind of asking sometimes for those additional resources is really helpful

00:14:49.539 --> 00:14:54.099
to get the full vision. And if there's a lot of disconnect between the business, sometimes

00:14:54.340 --> 00:15:01.059
that's a sign in and of itself. Thank you. Rick, I see you had asked a question

00:15:01.059 --> 00:15:07.140
in the chat a bit earlier. Do you want to go next? Well, thank you, everyone. Good morning, Jamie.

00:15:08.820 --> 00:15:14.260
I'm really intrigued with the fact that you're working now in a highly regulated industry.

00:15:14.260 --> 00:15:20.500
My question deals with how did you obtain the domain expertise to complement your expertise

00:15:20.500 --> 00:15:26.260
as a data scientist? How long did that take? And when did you feel like you were an expert

00:15:26.260 --> 00:15:32.260
in the domain? Your thoughts? No, no, it's a great question. And it's something I actually,

00:15:32.260 --> 00:15:36.500
I would say I have a little bit of my tech background to thank for that. So I started

00:15:36.500 --> 00:15:41.859
my career at Forrester Research, which is like a market research firm. So going into

00:15:43.219 --> 00:15:47.460
that type of work, we would always pay a lot of attention to having to upskill really quickly

00:15:47.460 --> 00:15:52.260
on the needs of our customers. And so when I moved into insurance, I was building models for

00:15:52.260 --> 00:15:57.299
initially for underwriters. So the people that pick the initial price for the policy,

00:15:57.299 --> 00:16:01.380
and I had no knowledge of what underwriting was. So I actually did go get certified as an underwriter

00:16:02.179 --> 00:16:07.460
through a process called the CPCU. So property casualty underwriter certification. And

00:16:08.099 --> 00:16:13.140
that was really beneficial, not just because it gave me a basic knowledge of what underwriters do,

00:16:13.140 --> 00:16:17.700
it was also helpful, because I could go to their conferences, and you get no better feedback than

00:16:17.700 --> 00:16:21.380
when you are at a conference with underwriters, and you announce that you are a data scientist,

00:16:21.380 --> 00:16:25.619
building the models that they have to deal with every day. And it's not the kind of feedback you

00:16:25.619 --> 00:16:29.859
get formally in the business environment. It's the kind of feedback where I hate this and this and

00:16:29.859 --> 00:16:36.340
this, and you get a lot of information. And I also understood, I mean, all of the data and insurance,

00:16:36.340 --> 00:16:40.820
something I love about it is my backgrounds in survey data, and all data and insurance is survey

