data, a claims adjuster put it in, you put it in, like, think about the last time you answered that

00:16:44.979 --> 00:16:50.659
questionnaire, you kind of fudged it a little bit, maybe. And so a lot of what we're doing when we

00:16:50.659 --> 00:16:56.419
clean the data is we do have to understand the business expertise. I also do a lot of like kind

00:16:56.419 --> 00:17:01.780
of trying to mix across the business. So I love to do a shadow, like job shadowing, a claims adjuster

00:17:01.780 --> 00:17:06.420
job shadowing, various folks across the business will really help. And then the final piece is,

00:17:06.420 --> 00:17:11.140
I think, as a data scientist, you're used to being kind of like, smarter person in the room,

00:17:11.140 --> 00:17:16.180
know everything. When you go into a business environment like this, it's important to

00:17:16.180 --> 00:17:20.739
lean into being the dumbest person in the room. And understand that, especially with historic

00:17:20.739 --> 00:17:24.579
processes, and this was a big one for me, when I first got in there, I was like, well, this is a

00:17:24.579 --> 00:17:29.540
stupid way to do it. This is a stupid way to do it. Why do they do it that way? And as I started to

00:17:29.540 --> 00:17:33.380
ask questions, it came about that, like, maybe there's a regulatory piece that was why they

00:17:33.380 --> 00:17:37.540
were doing it that way. Or for example, when I was at Lincoln, we had one thing where we were

00:17:37.540 --> 00:17:41.540
sending out these really expensive mailings. And I was like, why don't we just email this,

00:17:41.540 --> 00:17:45.380
it's so much faster, we actually know if they get hit back. And it was a regulatory constraint,

00:17:45.380 --> 00:17:49.939
there was a regulatory requirement around a physical piece of paper. And so that means that

00:17:49.939 --> 00:17:54.020
you need to be able to partner across the business to get over that constraint to get the adoption

00:17:54.020 --> 00:17:58.819
you need. So really asking those questions and coming in with rather than kind of like, I know

00:17:58.819 --> 00:18:03.780
better, coming in with curiosity, I think helps a lot. I will never know as much as our product

00:18:03.780 --> 00:18:11.780
folks. So really working with them too. Jamie, you have very keen insights. And I'm now a retired

00:18:11.780 --> 00:18:16.260
university faculty member, as well as a practitioner in industry for four decades.

00:18:18.819 --> 00:18:25.140
In your university hat, your adjunct hat, do you mentor your students to take similar approaches?

00:18:25.140 --> 00:18:31.540
I really commend your insight in obtaining that certification you mentioned. And things like that,

00:18:31.540 --> 00:18:38.819
are you advising your students to do similar things in their careers? Yeah, so from my perspective,

00:18:38.819 --> 00:18:42.579
like at the end of the day, the data is the most important thing, right? You can use any model,

