00:22:53.459 --> 00:22:58.739
I'm, you know, I've been doing this job for 30 years, I know exactly how to do it in SAS. SAS

00:22:58.739 --> 00:23:02.739
has great customer support. And you're expecting me to download this tool that I don't even know

00:23:02.739 --> 00:23:07.219
how to download. And where does the notebook live? I don't understand it. And so a lot of that,

00:23:07.219 --> 00:23:12.339
to me is really proactively being aggressive with training to make people feel comfortable.

00:23:12.339 --> 00:23:16.339
Because if you just give it to people and expect them to go back to their desks, like ideally,

00:23:16.339 --> 00:23:21.380
data scientists, a lot of curiosity, they would just go and break things. But people get nervous

00:23:21.380 --> 00:23:24.979
and people get kind of especially if you're known for being really good in your space. And then

00:23:24.979 --> 00:23:30.739
suddenly, you don't know a new code platform that can be really scary. I would say also,

00:23:31.619 --> 00:23:36.819
you know, with SAS, some of the some of the stuff that SAS has innate in it is really helpful for

00:23:36.819 --> 00:23:41.540
something like an insurer, because the packages aren't open source, which means that they have

00:23:41.540 --> 00:23:46.579
to be tested really extensively before they can get pushed out. And that's a really big risk when

00:23:46.579 --> 00:23:52.819
you move to open source code. Because and I talked back to that documentation, we have to have really

00:23:52.819 --> 00:23:57.300
good documentation, like yaml files and things like that around what was the environment we were

00:23:57.300 --> 00:24:01.300
using at the time we built this code, because when we go back to refresh it, we want to still be able

00:24:01.300 --> 00:24:06.500
to run it. And that's one of the risks of open source. So it does require a lot more analysis

00:24:06.500 --> 00:24:10.579
of the packages explaining that, like your SAS code, if you go back and run it 20 years later,

00:24:10.579 --> 00:24:16.260
it will still run, guarantee you, versus your Python code, you run it 20 years later,

00:24:16.979 --> 00:24:20.420
it's not going to work, all your packages are going to have dependencies, same thing with R.

00:24:21.219 --> 00:24:26.579
So really being aware of that. And picking some of the packages that are really more comfortable

00:24:26.579 --> 00:24:30.260
to use, I feel like Rachel probably has tons of experience with this, because their whole

00:24:31.300 --> 00:24:36.339
environment is, is easy to use packages that are great for different types of techniques and kind

00:24:36.339 --> 00:24:40.819
of help people edge the way in. But really, yeah, I'd say it's that training education piece. And

00:24:40.819 --> 00:24:45.060
there is part of it is just there's a lot of legacy code that runs and nobody quite knows

00:24:45.060 --> 00:24:50.500
who built it. And nobody quite knows why it runs, but it does. So breaking that apart takes a lot

00:24:50.500 --> 00:24:55.780
more effort. And it doesn't show a measurable outcome, necessarily. Like, if you fix it all

00:24:55.780 --> 00:25:00.579
and put it in a new technology, the code still just runs. So you do have to kind of balance those

00:25:00.579 --> 00:25:11.380
things. Thank you so much. Let's see, let me jump back to a few questions on earlier. Renhua,

00:25:11.939 --> 00:25:17.780
I know you had a question earlier about the migration to the cloud. Do you want to jump in?

00:25:22.339 --> 00:25:28.979
And the question was around what has been most challenging about using cloud, or maybe I'll add

