about the migration to the cloud for an insurance company. Yeah, I think it was the insurance data,

00:25:37.300 --> 00:25:45.380
all that kind of stuff is regulated and related to personal data, you know, very sensitive data.

00:25:45.380 --> 00:25:53.140
So I was thinking how you guys deal with that data, or what's the kind of challenge for you,

00:25:53.699 --> 00:25:59.300
you know, if you build a model from the beginning to the end, everything in the cloud,

00:26:00.099 --> 00:26:05.699
how do you deal with that, make sure not get a, you know, issue for the

00:26:07.300 --> 00:26:14.819
regulation or other stuff? Yeah. So insurance is, and most of the regulated industries are special

00:26:14.819 --> 00:26:19.780
in that we use a lot of like PII, which is like kind of personally identifiable information. And

00:26:19.780 --> 00:26:23.459
sometimes we have health information, we have social security numbers, we have all sorts of

00:26:23.459 --> 00:26:29.619
things like that. There's a couple pieces to that equation. The first is that you're working with IT

00:26:29.619 --> 00:26:34.500
and you have really good data governance, because you can mask a lot of those fields, you don't need

00:26:34.500 --> 00:26:39.780
them, you can create like IDs to replace things like social security, and then have it crosswalk

00:26:39.780 --> 00:26:44.260
back later if you needed it. So things like that you don't actually need to have in the cloud

00:26:44.260 --> 00:26:48.579
environment that everyone has access to if you have good and I again, I always say it goes back

00:26:48.579 --> 00:26:53.380
to the data. If you have good kind of data standards around your governance, you can take

00:26:53.380 --> 00:26:57.060
out a lot of the information that you don't need. Now you still typically do have a lot of

00:26:57.060 --> 00:27:02.979
information that is private. So we do have a lot of different compliance pieces, but

00:27:02.979 --> 00:27:06.900
one of the things I like to remind people of is just because you have it on local doesn't mean

00:27:06.900 --> 00:27:15.300
it's secure. And I think people tend to forget like, yeah, it's on John's machine over there

00:27:15.380 --> 00:27:21.219
and Sam's machine over there. And it's getting sent by email, you know, that isn't necessarily

00:27:21.219 --> 00:27:26.819
more secure than putting it in like an AWS or Google Cloud or Azure environment. In those

00:27:26.819 --> 00:27:32.260
environments, we can really restrict security and add permissions and know who's touched data when.

00:27:32.260 --> 00:27:37.219
And so a lot of those things are how I make the case around it. But it is definitely it's a big,

00:27:37.219 --> 00:27:41.459
it's a big step for people. And I think comparing it back to the current state and really making

00:27:41.459 --> 00:27:44.260
people aware of what the current state is does help.

00:27:48.339 --> 00:27:53.939
Do you actually follow on to that too? I know there's something that came up in a hangout with

00:27:53.939 --> 00:28:00.420
Biogen on like the data governance or data stewardship piece. How do you, I guess,

00:28:00.420 --> 00:28:05.140
come up with best practices for how people handle work on their desktop or

00:28:05.540 --> 00:28:13.939
the ways that they're handling data? Yeah, it's a really good question. I was lucky enough to

00:28:13.939 --> 00:28:19.140
initially grow up in a very strict data culture in my first role at Liberty Mutual, where we had

00:28:19.140 --> 00:28:24.979
really high standards. And so for me, a lot of it has been repeating those standards over and over

00:28:24.979 --> 00:28:30.900
and over again. But I also go back to actually in the insurance industry, one of the things that's

00:28:31.859 --> 00:28:37.060
really riling some things up right now is the National Association of Insurance Commissioners

00:28:37.060 --> 00:28:41.939
just released their letter on AI, how they're thinking about AI, how they're thinking about

00:28:41.939 --> 00:28:47.780
data. And we really always want to be following like a lot of those standards. And I think that

00:28:47.780 --> 00:28:52.579
goes back a lot to knowing what's in your data, knowing what your different fields are, knowing

00:28:52.579 --> 00:28:59.459
how much you actually need them, and kind of how you are, even if you have like a data dictionary,

00:28:59.540 --> 00:29:04.420
do you understand which fields are sensitive and which fields aren't? Or do you have basic protocols

00:29:04.420 --> 00:29:08.660
to not email your data? And kind of just a little bit of awareness, because I think,

00:29:08.660 --> 00:29:13.060
especially coming out of school, which I got a lot of folks that are like PhDs when I hire,

00:29:13.699 --> 00:29:17.699
and they're used to like data that's already cleaned or anonymized, or can be emailed around

00:29:17.699 --> 00:29:22.339
between different groups, or can be uploaded to the Google share whatnot. And our data really

00:29:22.339 --> 00:29:27.219
doesn't act like that. We have to be a lot more strict. So a lot of it is creating that protocol

00:29:27.219 --> 00:29:31.140
around, this is the process, this is how we follow it. If you're doing work on your machine,

00:29:31.140 --> 00:29:35.859
are you saving it back? Are you, you know, doing a pull and a push request and making sure you're

00:29:35.859 --> 00:29:41.300
saving it back every day? And kind of that is a big piece of it. Because we do a lot of testing

00:29:41.300 --> 00:29:46.819
locally, just before you kind of run something up all the time. So that's really push and pull

00:29:46.819 --> 00:29:51.300
requests. And I've definitely gotten people before on that. I think once you make the mistake of not

00:29:51.300 --> 00:29:55.619
doing it, and you lose something, you never make that mistake again. But that's definitely a big

00:29:55.619 --> 00:30:02.420
piece of it. Thank you. I know there was just an anonymous question that came in while you're

00:30:02.420 --> 00:30:09.859
answering that too, which was, how do you keep track of which fields are sensitive? So PII or PHI,

00:30:09.859 --> 00:30:14.500
how do you ensure those fields are not shared outside of having documentation in place?

00:30:16.099 --> 00:30:20.900
I think that definitely depends on the scale of your organization. So if you're like a larger

00:30:20.900 --> 00:30:25.619
organization, you might have a tool like Snowflake or some other sort of software where it's really

00:30:25.619 --> 00:30:32.099
easy to like tag things and label them. With a lot of insurance data, a lot of it's like historic

00:30:32.099 --> 00:30:36.819
files that have been stored somewhere or some of it's like uploaded at specific times. So

00:30:37.859 --> 00:30:42.979
with the documentation piece, I think it's really about documentation and then kind of

00:30:42.979 --> 00:30:47.380
masking a lot of things as you push them out. So doing it at the first step rather than at

00:30:47.380 --> 00:30:51.380
the every model step, and then having people come back and request it if they need it. So

00:30:51.380 --> 00:30:55.939
instead of like generally having one modeling data set that everyone can work from, you have

00:30:55.939 --> 00:31:00.500
the set that's already been transformed kind of hidden. And then if people need those fields,

00:31:00.500 --> 00:31:05.140
they can come to you rather than leaving the fields in as default. So sensitive fields we

00:31:05.140 --> 00:31:09.140
tend to remove. It's also really important in highly regulated industries to know there's

00:31:09.140 --> 00:31:13.459
some fields you can never have, even if a vendor tries to send them to you. And those include all

00:31:13.459 --> 00:31:19.140
the protected class information. So just kind of being really aware of that. And if there's an

00:31:19.140 --> 00:31:22.260
issue, letting people know that we're in an environment where they can come and tell you

00:31:22.260 --> 00:31:27.939
they've made a mistake. Because the worst thing is to pull that data over and then to keep having it

00:31:27.939 --> 00:31:33.060
rather than to flag it. So it's kind of that culture around, hey, I can raise my hand and

00:31:33.060 --> 00:31:39.219
let you know I accidentally had this open data or did this is really important. Thank you. I'm

