absolutely a dynamic that I'm navigating. And I like to be the first mover and then prove that

00:32:44.099 --> 00:32:49.140
we've got a business case that we can save money. I always think about with that, if I'm in the

00:32:49.140 --> 00:32:54.819
slower group, the first thing I think about is what is something I first look at the company

00:32:54.819 --> 00:32:59.939
goals for the year, right? So like, or organizational goals for the three-year period, whatever they are.

00:32:59.939 --> 00:33:04.260
And then I try to think about if there's any projects that we're working on that would make

00:33:04.260 --> 00:33:09.300
a material impact to those goals. And usually it's a cost savings or a revenue generation item.

00:33:09.939 --> 00:33:16.020
And then I use that project to try to justify why I need new tech. And that's the only way I've ever

00:33:16.020 --> 00:33:22.579
seen it work is really focusing on that piece of like, this tech is going to drive this ROI and

00:33:22.579 --> 00:33:26.339
it's going to cost us money, but it's also going to save us this much money. And it ties to your

00:33:26.900 --> 00:33:33.780
objectives up here is really how we make noise on that. And then when you're part of the

00:33:33.780 --> 00:33:38.420
company is doing that and seeing success, you're able to kind of say like, hey, why haven't they

00:33:39.699 --> 00:33:46.660
adopted it? But I tend to think of it as if you can like kind of a rising tide rises all boats,

00:33:46.660 --> 00:33:51.859
right? So if you're moving up and you're getting new technology, like being the people that upskill

00:33:51.859 --> 00:33:55.859
and train and help the other departments is great. If they don't want to come along for the ride

00:33:55.859 --> 00:34:00.099
though, they don't have to, and you don't need to drag them. Dragging them can like, I used to try

00:34:00.099 --> 00:34:04.660
to do that like earlier in my career, and that can really drive you down and slow your progress.

