is around resource capacity planning. So the idea that managers sort of submit something early on

00:35:44.020 --> 00:35:51.139
that says this person's going to be spending this many hours on a project and then trying

00:35:51.139 --> 00:35:56.820
to reconcile that with what that resource actually does submit and sort of plan ahead to

00:35:56.820 --> 00:36:02.820
try to line up those expectations about where people are going to be, which projects people

00:36:02.820 --> 00:36:09.300
are going to be spending their time on. So it's kind of a fun one. Yeah, that's definitely a fun

00:36:09.300 --> 00:36:13.620
one, and one thing I would caution is if you can make sure that your metrics have kind of

00:36:14.260 --> 00:36:20.820
two levels, and what I mean by that is everyone who works in any environment is great at optimizing

00:36:20.820 --> 00:36:25.939
the benefit to them. So in a call center, for example, if you optimize the number of calls taken,

00:36:25.939 --> 00:36:30.739
people will actually just start hanging up on customers to get more calls taken, and if you

00:36:30.739 --> 00:36:36.260
optimize on like a quality metric, people will stay on the phone as long as possible and make

