00:37:40.580 --> 00:37:45.139
Thank you. Okay, Rick, I see you asked a question with the star, so I'll read it,

00:37:45.219 --> 00:37:50.179
but Jamie, is the digital transformation initiative company-wide or is the effort

00:37:50.179 --> 00:37:55.540
restricted to the data science function? Also, to what degree are future-ish data science

00:37:55.540 --> 00:38:05.379
considerations considered in this roadmap? Sure, so the initiative is technically company-wide,

00:38:05.379 --> 00:38:11.300
but I am front-running my area in it, so the company-wide initiative, it looks like it will

00:38:11.300 --> 00:38:16.979
probably take another few more months to even get an idea of what tool suite they're going to

00:38:16.979 --> 00:38:22.179
go with. They're doing a lot of analysis. They're doing a lot of thinking, so I offered to be a test

00:38:22.179 --> 00:38:26.820
guinea pig and said, what if we just front-run you guys? We'll go in there. We'll test and learn.

00:38:26.820 --> 00:38:32.739
We'll use everything, so it is technically a global initiative coming, but our initiative,

00:38:32.739 --> 00:38:40.100
we're alone for probably the first couple years. In terms of the broader piece, I think one of

00:38:40.100 --> 00:38:44.100
the things that's really powerful with getting leadership on board with the level of spend you

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:49.699
have to use to get and migrate into something like a cloud environment is that new age stuff, right?

00:38:50.340 --> 00:38:56.580
They love the buzz, the AI, the gen AI, the future of whatever, and if you think about something like,

00:38:56.580 --> 00:39:01.620
for example, home insurance, today we might use a lot of features that are point in time,

00:39:01.620 --> 00:39:06.100
like the square footage of your house, but if you think about the devices you have in your home

00:39:06.100 --> 00:39:12.260
today, in the future we might want to be able to take actions based on real-time data, and we can't

00:39:12.260 --> 00:39:17.139
do that with the infrastructure we have today, and so a lot of it is around kind of justifying.

00:39:17.139 --> 00:39:21.139
We need to start building now if we want to be able to do that in five or six years, and that's

00:39:21.139 --> 00:39:24.899
the unfortunate truth. Even if we wanted to do it in a decade, we'd probably have to start building

00:39:24.899 --> 00:39:30.179
now, so that case resonates a little bit more with the long-term planning, like executive suite versus

00:39:30.179 --> 00:39:34.899
the case of like today. I really just need them to be able to have enough processing power,

00:39:34.899 --> 00:39:42.820
right? Really basic things. Thank you. Someone had sent me a direct question around

00:39:42.820 --> 00:39:50.580
what you look for when hiring, so somebody just getting out of school, but I also wanted to add

00:39:50.580 --> 00:39:55.780
into this because I saw that you were hiring a data engineer recently, and so I thought it would

00:39:55.780 --> 00:40:00.580
also be good to chat a little bit about that and just understand what are you looking for in that

00:40:00.659 --> 00:40:07.379
role? Sure, so first kind of in general hiring, the number one thing I look for is curiosity.

00:40:08.419 --> 00:40:12.739
I think that you can learn, if you already know a programming language, you can learn any other

00:40:12.739 --> 00:40:17.780
language if you're curious, but I cannot necessarily teach you to be the kind of person

00:40:17.780 --> 00:40:23.219
that sees a weird pattern in the data and wants to know more. I think that that's kind of like

00:40:23.219 --> 00:40:27.219
you're either that kind of person or you're like, oh man, there's a weird pattern. I wish it would

00:40:27.219 --> 00:40:33.540
go away, and so that's really what I look for when I hire, especially for data scientists,

00:40:33.540 --> 00:40:39.540
is the drive to understand the why of what they're seeing and that test and learn kind of interest.

00:40:40.820 --> 00:40:45.060
When I think about the data engineer role that we're hiring, I'm really excited about it because

00:40:45.860 --> 00:40:50.179
we have historically never had any data engineer roles, and this is a really common thing at lots

00:40:50.179 --> 00:40:54.899
of companies because they hire a bunch of data scientists and they're like, aren't you data

00:40:54.899 --> 00:41:00.979
scientists? Why can't you ingest and prep the data as well as building the models? I think I

00:41:00.979 --> 00:41:06.820
like to think of data scientists as the people that could play a data engineer on TV. They know

00:41:06.820 --> 00:41:12.340
enough to be dangerous and also to make really badly unoptimized pipelines. It's a totally

00:41:12.340 --> 00:41:16.179
different skill set, especially as we move into some of these cloud technologies. There's so much

00:41:16.179 --> 00:41:22.659
really cool, interesting optimization to be done, and you need to understand what to ask for to do

00:41:22.659 --> 00:41:27.300
that, especially with your IT partners. You need to understand what the capabilities are because you

00:41:27.300 --> 00:41:32.899
won't always have, you know, in Excel or in SAS, you would have almost total control of everything

00:41:32.899 --> 00:41:37.300
that was happening. In an environment like AWS, you really have to rely on your infrastructure

00:41:37.300 --> 00:41:43.939
people, and they don't necessarily know what's best for things like a data pipeline. So that

00:41:43.939 --> 00:41:49.139
is really what that role is about, is rethinking the way we ingest our data and process it,

00:41:49.139 --> 00:41:54.100
especially so that we can do it in a way that's automated. There's so many good new tools now

00:41:54.820 --> 00:41:59.139
to look at things like flagging you're missing, like identifying imputation opportunities, and

00:41:59.139 --> 00:42:05.780
then actually doing it and keeping a great record of it in the system. So I really think that that's

00:42:05.780 --> 00:42:11.540
important. I don't know if that answered all the questions. Yeah, thank you so much.

00:42:12.419 --> 00:42:17.139
Verisa, I see you asked a question. Want to jump in here with the onboarding question?

00:42:18.899 --> 00:42:23.699
Sure, thanks. I just, yeah, following up on the hiring questions, I was just wondering

00:42:23.699 --> 00:42:28.260
what are the things that you do to onboard your new data scientists? Like, I work in insurance

00:42:28.260 --> 00:42:32.739
as well, and I know when people come in, they're sort of a little shocked at the amount of data

00:42:32.739 --> 00:42:37.780
that we've got in all of the different topics that everything encompasses, compared to a lot

00:42:37.780 --> 00:42:44.179
of different industries. Yeah. What does that look like for you? Absolutely. It's a great question.

00:42:44.179 --> 00:42:49.780
I think the number one thing, I go back to having really good historic documentation and holding my

00:42:49.780 --> 00:42:55.300
team to a certain standard makes onboarding very easy, because we have the documentation. Now,

00:42:56.179 --> 00:43:00.899
for example, I moved to Plymouth about six months ago. I don't have that legacy of me being

00:43:01.459 --> 00:43:08.260
too aggressive on documentation historically. So, a couple of things. Going back to one of the

00:43:08.260 --> 00:43:11.379
earlier questions, I really think business knowledge is important. So, one of the first

00:43:11.379 --> 00:43:16.500
things I have data science folks do is shadow a bunch of the key business users that create the

00:43:16.500 --> 00:43:21.060
data that they're using. So, for example, if they're working in an agency space, I have them

00:43:21.060 --> 00:43:25.620
go watch the agents and put whatever they're inputting. Same thing with a claims adjuster

00:43:25.620 --> 00:43:29.379
or an underwriter. I'll have them do a shadow in the first couple weeks, understand that person's

00:43:29.379 --> 00:43:34.179
role, understand the intricacies of the data. So then when they get in the data, they recognize,

00:43:34.179 --> 00:43:40.179
oh, here's what I'm looking at, what I'm trying to see. I'll always get them a buddy on the product

00:43:40.179 --> 00:43:44.739
side or someone somewhere else in the business. Those people usually love to hear more about data

00:43:44.739 --> 00:43:49.780
science, and they get the added benefit of this person learning more, someone they can go to

00:43:49.780 --> 00:43:55.060
really quickly for business side questions. And then just documentation, documentation,

00:43:55.060 --> 00:43:59.459
documentation. So, I usually like to give them a tiny project that uses the data

00:43:59.459 --> 00:44:04.020
that we like to use, but in a way where they'll kind of find some issues and errors that I can

00:44:04.020 --> 00:44:09.139
know about already and expect to see how they treat them just to get a feel for them too, right?

00:44:09.139 --> 00:44:13.620
When I hire them, all I know about you is what you've told me. I don't actually know like your

00:44:13.620 --> 00:44:17.860
quality, what your gaps are, what you're good at. So, giving a little project where I kind of know

00:44:17.860 --> 00:44:21.780
where the outcome should fall can really help me identify, okay, here's where you're good,

00:44:21.780 --> 00:44:26.979
here's the growth areas I need from you. And so, I'd say those are a few things that we do on

00:44:26.979 --> 00:44:37.139
onboarding. Yeah. I really love the point about shadowing, and I see Libby had commented about

00:44:37.699 --> 00:44:44.100
literally begging to shadow some users, but being told no. Did you have to go through anything

00:44:44.100 --> 00:44:51.459
internally to set that up, or how does that work? Yeah, it's definitely a, I know when I first

00:44:51.540 --> 00:44:56.659
started in insurance, the first time I asked to shadow an underwriter, my manager looked at me

00:44:56.659 --> 00:45:02.659
like I was insane. They were like, no, we don't let the data people near the underwriters. And

00:45:03.620 --> 00:45:09.699
I think that that's really a conversation you should be, the data science leaders that you have

00:45:09.699 --> 00:45:13.780
should be having with their peers. Like, I think a lot of times the reason that we don't get

00:45:13.780 --> 00:45:18.979
adoption is because people don't think that we understand the work that they do. And showing

00:45:18.979 --> 00:45:24.979
that curiosity, I have almost never had a peer across the business turn me down when I say,

00:45:24.979 --> 00:45:29.300
I really want my people to understand this better because I want them to be able to make the best

00:45:29.300 --> 00:45:33.060
outcome for you, and I feel like we don't understand what you do effectively. They're

00:45:33.060 --> 00:45:38.020
always going to agree that we don't understand what they do. So, that's a much better way to

00:45:38.020 --> 00:45:42.659
do it. But again, if you can't get that from inside your company, I would totally recommend

00:45:42.659 --> 00:45:47.459
going to the professional networks. So, there's like networks of claims adjusters, there's like

00:45:47.459 --> 00:45:51.459
the underwriting network that I'm a part of. They have like all sorts of different meetups and

00:45:51.459 --> 00:45:55.219
trainings and things like that. And you can go and meet, you know, underwriters from some other

00:45:55.219 --> 00:45:58.979
company if the ones from your company won't talk to you. So, that does take a little bit of a

00:45:58.979 --> 00:46:04.580
proactive push and a little bit of research. But that piece, if you can't get it internally,

00:46:04.580 --> 00:46:08.979
I would definitely push to get it externally. And if your manager is not pushing for it,

00:46:08.979 --> 00:46:15.939
I mean, I would consider a kind of, do they have the right vision? And if they don't, sometimes

00:46:15.939 --> 00:46:21.139
data science managers can be very, very technical and not as good at this particular area. And that's

00:46:21.139 --> 00:46:25.139
when it's really helpful to have a buddy on the product team who maybe their manager can go have

00:46:25.139 --> 00:46:32.500
that conversation. Would they have like a better relationship? Yeah. Thank you so much.

00:46:34.179 --> 00:46:37.939
Michael, you asked a question here in the chat a little bit earlier. Want to jump in?

00:46:39.060 --> 00:46:42.419
Yeah, no, I was just curious when she mentioned, I'm doing a little market research on,

00:46:42.419 --> 00:46:47.379
I've got a lot of background in data de-identification, particularly in PHI. But

00:46:47.379 --> 00:46:51.860
any types of things you'd like to see, I think particularly with LLMs, there's a lot of

00:46:51.860 --> 00:46:55.780
background in working with structured data and de-identification when it comes to unstructured

00:46:55.780 --> 00:47:00.580
data. It's kind of like, if you follow a lot of the buzz about vector databases, things like that,

00:47:00.580 --> 00:47:04.580
it's kind of like the holy grail. Everyone's looking for a way to find some type of

00:47:04.580 --> 00:47:10.340
de-identification, universal, you know, solve everything problem. So, you could easily manage

00:47:10.340 --> 00:47:17.139
PHI and DID with unstructured data, which there's some things out there. There's nothing really

00:47:17.139 --> 00:47:22.020
universal just yet. There's a few offerings. I know the Microsoft is claiming they have a tool

00:47:22.020 --> 00:47:26.340
that you can use, but you have to put it into their cloud. So, having like a local model versus

00:47:26.340 --> 00:47:30.979
having something in a third party. And I was just curious what types of things, I know that I'm

00:47:30.979 --> 00:47:35.379
asking a very broad, broad question, but it's kind of like my next startup I'm planning on. So,

00:47:35.939 --> 00:47:39.459
that's why I would love to get your ideas of what you would think would be very useful in

00:47:39.459 --> 00:47:46.020
the insurance business. Yeah. So, I think it's helpful to tell a story. So, if you guys remember,

00:47:46.020 --> 00:47:51.379
Obama had a chief data scientist, DJ Patil. And when he left his role, he initially decided he

00:47:51.379 --> 00:47:56.500
was going to tackle the problem of data and insurance. And he was going to create like

00:47:56.500 --> 00:48:01.540
some sort of system to handle all the data that we have in all these and really streamline it and

00:48:01.540 --> 00:48:08.500
get it all in a single source and really improve outcomes that way. And then he gave a talk maybe

00:48:08.500 --> 00:48:12.659
a year later and he said, you know, we got there and we realized all the data is in PDFs and maybe

00:48:12.659 --> 00:48:18.580
this isn't what we want to tackle. And you've similarly seen Amazon recently did a foray into

00:48:18.580 --> 00:48:22.659
an insurance. They shut it down like a couple months later. They just shut down the UK operation,

00:48:22.659 --> 00:48:32.260
Google, same thing. The data problem in these highly regulated industries is enormous. And it's

00:48:32.260 --> 00:48:37.139
very, very challenging. And the first stage of it, like you're thinking of like the fourth stage

00:48:37.620 --> 00:48:42.419
and the first stage hasn't even happened. The aggregation, effectively aggregating and combining

00:48:42.419 --> 00:48:46.340
data across different sources hasn't even happened yet. And there's a couple startups starting to do

00:48:46.340 --> 00:48:50.419
this in like the health space where they aggregate like your health data across all your various

00:48:50.419 --> 00:48:54.899
technologies, like your watch and your whatever, whatever. But like, if you think about insurance,

00:48:54.899 --> 00:48:59.860
we collect data from the motor vehicle records. We collect data from your health, you know,

00:48:59.860 --> 00:49:04.020
different types of doctors and providers. We collect data from all these places where their

00:49:04.020 --> 00:49:08.659
data is actually really bad. And we don't have good system linkages and all this, like think

00:49:08.659 --> 00:49:14.500
about trying to get your hospital records and what that data looks like. And so to me, like the first

00:49:14.500 --> 00:49:19.540
problem to be solved is not even masking it, it's getting it and putting it in a format that's

00:49:19.540 --> 00:49:24.739
actually usable and consistent from all these different places. And we've seen some providers

00:49:24.739 --> 00:49:29.620
do that in very specific spaces, like prescription data. There's a provider that has worked to like

00:49:29.620 --> 00:49:33.459
aggregate all of that. Or like motor vehicle records, there's a provider that has worked

00:49:33.459 --> 00:49:38.500
to aggregate, but those pieces to me have to be answered. And when you answer those pieces well,

00:49:38.500 --> 00:49:42.979
then when you start doing these giant kind of other types of models and structures,

00:49:42.979 --> 00:49:50.100
you actually have the foundation to be able to tag, flag, whatever, versus trying to start from

00:49:50.100 --> 00:49:54.179
like step four. I don't know, that's a personal opinion on a broad subject, but-

00:49:54.739 --> 00:49:58.100
I think I was just gonna give a background. I've been focused the last several years,

00:49:58.100 --> 00:50:01.379
my current, I've just started my new gig, but last several years I've been in a healthcare

00:50:01.379 --> 00:50:06.580
company where that is what we were doing, taking like claims and EHR, practice management data,

00:50:06.580 --> 00:50:11.620
pharmacy data, et cetera, and building a common data model. There's tools like OMOP and others,

00:50:11.620 --> 00:50:16.179
you know, that are used in the healthcare side. I can't necessarily say all of insurance, but

00:50:16.179 --> 00:50:19.860
the idea, the next dilemma then is, so now you've got this common model where it's the

00:50:19.860 --> 00:50:23.379
holy grail that you're trying to get to is a large data set that can be used to build

00:50:23.379 --> 00:50:27.699
predictive modeling, get towards precision medicine. Instead of having all the patients

00:50:27.699 --> 00:50:31.860
in a hospital, you could have like every breast cancer patient in America in a data set and you

00:50:31.860 --> 00:50:36.659
could get really, really fine-tuned analysis and that's the holy grail. But to get there,

00:50:36.659 --> 00:50:41.300
once you get this big data repository, you find out like, okay, we can handle the structured data,

00:50:41.300 --> 00:50:45.540
we can do de-identification on that. Now comes the unstructured, all the doctor's notes, all the other

00:50:45.540 --> 00:50:50.899
lab results, the PDFs, as you said, everything's in a PDF and they all have proprietary mechanisms

00:50:50.899 --> 00:50:54.659
to try to decode them. And there's work being done there, but then once you get to that, it's like,

00:50:54.659 --> 00:51:00.899
okay, how do we de-identify this and how do we do it reliably? Yeah. And there's some really cool

00:51:00.899 --> 00:51:05.540
startups doing work in the space of pulling data off PDFs and even doctor's terrible handwriting,

00:51:05.540 --> 00:51:11.620
really cool, like LLM, Gen AI work on that, some of them local to Boston. So that is really

00:51:11.620 --> 00:51:16.820
exciting to me because that five years ago, nobody was doing that. Yeah. Thank you for your answer.

00:51:18.179 --> 00:51:23.620
Jacob, I see you had a question around building data pipelines. Want to jump in?

00:51:24.899 --> 00:51:30.419
Yeah, I guess it's more kind of a general question of, have you ever heard of a data

00:51:30.419 --> 00:51:36.100
scientist cross-training as a data engineer? Yeah. Oh my gosh. A hundred percent. I have people

00:51:36.100 --> 00:51:42.739
going back and forth both directions. You do need to understand, I think that there

00:51:42.739 --> 00:51:51.219
should be cross-training period. Back when I went back to school to get my master's,

00:51:51.219 --> 00:51:55.139
a bunch of the courses I actually took at that point were in database infrastructure,

00:51:55.939 --> 00:52:00.580
which is less relevant now, but being able to understand the database infrastructure really

00:52:00.580 --> 00:52:05.780
helps with implementation. And if you can ask the right questions and use the same language as IT,

00:52:05.780 --> 00:52:10.340
that's super helpful. And I like those skills are so useful back and forth. And I could definitely

00:52:10.340 --> 00:52:17.219
see kind of cross-training, especially because a lot of times, I think for the last decade or so,

00:52:17.939 --> 00:52:22.580
the data scientist terminology has been kind of viewed as sexier than the data engineering

00:52:22.580 --> 00:52:26.020
terminology for no particular reason. They're both critical to the process.

00:52:26.020 --> 00:52:29.939
And so I think people would be very welcome to bring you the other direction. We usually have

00:52:29.939 --> 00:52:33.699
the opposite problem where you hire a data engineer and they only want to be a data scientist.

00:52:34.500 --> 00:52:36.580
So yeah, I would welcome someone going the other way.

00:52:38.419 --> 00:52:45.139
So in terms of getting that training or knowledge, would you recommend just talking to the subject

00:52:45.139 --> 00:52:49.300
matter experts in your company or are there any independent resources that you know of to

00:52:49.300 --> 00:52:54.340
get started? Yeah. I mean, I would start with kind of informational. The way I always start

00:52:54.340 --> 00:52:58.979
whenever anyone thinks about any development across job areas is some informational interviews

00:52:58.979 --> 00:53:03.780
with people doing that work, asking them what tools they use day-to-day, what is their job

00:53:03.780 --> 00:53:07.780
really like day-to-day. And I would do it across a few different companies. I would ask the data

00:53:07.780 --> 00:53:11.620
engineers at your company, but also really think about where it is you want to land.

00:53:11.620 --> 00:53:16.260
Because even if I think about data science, people ask me, how do I become a data scientist?

00:53:16.260 --> 00:53:20.899
I get that question all the time. And my response is, well, is it an insurance? Is it in tech?

00:53:20.899 --> 00:53:25.379
Is it in... Because in some of those spaces, you're going to want a PhD and a specialization.

00:53:25.379 --> 00:53:28.739
In some of those spaces, you're going to want... You can come right out of undergrad and do

00:53:29.379 --> 00:53:34.419
XYZ and you'll be working with certain types of techniques. So I would say data engineer

00:53:34.419 --> 00:53:39.540
means so many different things that I would really start to hone in first on what's your

00:53:39.540 --> 00:53:44.899
industry space and what does data engineer mean to you. And then where are those types of roles

00:53:44.899 --> 00:53:49.860
and how do I start working with that peer group? And then there's really great volunteer organizations.

00:53:49.860 --> 00:53:54.260
An example would be Code Across America, where you can come in and work on little projects.

00:53:55.379 --> 00:53:59.300
And there'll be other data engineers in the group where you can learn from them informally.

00:53:59.860 --> 00:54:04.500
That's just off the top of my head, but I think that kind of framework is how I think about it.

00:54:04.580 --> 00:54:06.340
Yeah, thanks. I'll check it out. I appreciate it.

00:54:06.340 --> 00:54:10.979
Yeah. Thank you. Jamie, there was an anonymous question I missed earlier,

00:54:12.020 --> 00:54:15.860
which was about migration to the cloud. And just ask me if you could share a little bit

00:54:15.860 --> 00:54:22.580
about the tools that you're using for that. So we happen to be like an AWS infrastructure

00:54:22.580 --> 00:54:28.500
company. No pros or cons there. I don't think I can share necessarily the proprietary tool

00:54:28.500 --> 00:54:36.419
set we use inside that. But I would say if you do decide to use AWS versus Google Cloud versus

00:54:36.419 --> 00:54:40.979
Azure, just be aware that AWS is like Legos. There's a bunch of pieces everywhere and you

00:54:40.979 --> 00:54:43.780
have to put them together the way you want them. And if you don't know how to do that,

00:54:44.340 --> 00:54:50.020
it can be really hard. So I would say we have lots of different Legos and then you can also hook in

00:54:50.020 --> 00:54:55.699
other different types of tools. If you go with something more like Azure, a lot of it's more

00:54:55.939 --> 00:55:01.379
pre-built, a little bit more predefined in Google Cloud. But yeah, we're using AWS as part of our

00:55:01.379 --> 00:55:07.060
tech stack. And then we have a bunch of other tools stacked in there. Well, thank you. As we

00:55:07.060 --> 00:55:13.379
get to the end here, I would love to ask you if you could share a piece of career advice that kind

00:55:13.379 --> 00:55:18.260
of sticks out to you in your mind, or maybe it's something you received or that you've given to

00:55:18.260 --> 00:55:25.139
someone on your team. Sure. So my biggest piece of career advice would be to lean in to being the

